{
  "Revenue is also called:": "",
  "Top line (the first line on an income statement)": "",
  "Gross profit, even when conditions shift": "",
  "Net profit when viewed through a simplified": "",
  "Bottom line without accounting": "",
  "Revenue appears as the first (top) line on an income statement, which is why it is commonly referred to as the 'top line.'": "",
  "Gross profit is calculated as:": "",
  "Revenue - Operating Expenses": "",
  "Revenue + COGS": "",
  "Revenue - Cost of Goods Sold": "",
  "Net Income + Taxes": "",
  "Gross profit equals revenue minus the cost of goods sold (COGS), representing the profit before operating expenses, taxes, and interest.": "",
  "A bakery sells $200,000 in goods with $80,000 in COGS. Gross profit =": "",
  "$280,000": "",
  "$200,000": "",
  "$80,000": "",
  "$120,000": "",
  "Gross profit = Revenue - COGS = $200,000 - $80,000 = $120,000.": "",
  "A positive net profit means the business:": "",
  "Broke even exactly": "",
  "Needs additional investment": "",
  "Lost money during the period": "",
  "Earned more than it spent (profitable)": "",
  "A positive net profit indicates the business's total revenues exceeded its total expenses during the reporting period, meaning the business was profitable.": "",
  "Operating expenses include all of the following EXCEPT:": "",
  "Marketing costs": "",
  "Administrative salaries": "",
  "Raw materials used in production": "",
  "Rent and utilities": "",
  "Raw materials used in production are classified as Cost of Goods Sold (COGS), not operating expenses. Operating expenses are overhead costs not directly tied to production.": "",
  "A negative net profit (net loss) means:": "",
  "Expenses exceeded revenue during the period": "",
  "The business has no debt": "",
  "The business is thriving": "",
  "Revenue was exactly zero": "",
  "A net loss occurs when total expenses exceed total revenues, meaning the business spent more than it earned during the reporting period.": "",
  "Depreciation expense is considered a non-cash expense because:": "",
  "No actual cash leaves the business when depreciation is recorded": "",
  "It involves a tax payment each period": "",
  "It increases revenue over time": "",
  "It only applies to service businesses": "",
  "Depreciation allocates the cost of a long-term asset over its useful life on the income statement, but no cash actually leaves the business each period when depreciation is recorded.": "",
  "COGS for a service business typically includes:": "",
  "Raw materials and manufacturing overhead": "",
  "Building rent and insurance": "",
  "Direct labor and supplies for delivering the service": "",
  "Marketing and advertising costs": "",
  "For service businesses, COGS includes the direct costs of providing the service, such as direct labor and supplies, rather than physical materials used in manufacturing.": "",
  "Net profit margin = $50,000 ÷ $200,000 =": "",
  "25%": "",
  "30%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "Net profit margin = Net profit / Revenue = $50,000 / $200,000 = 0.25, or 25%.": "",
  "A P&L (profit and loss) statement covers:": "",
  "A specific time period such as a month, quarter, or year": "",
  "Only the current day's activity": "",
  "The company's entire history since founding": "",
  "A single transaction only": "",
  "A profit and loss statement (income statement) reports financial performance over a defined period, such as a month, quarter, or fiscal year.": "",
  "What is 'revenue' in the context of a profit and loss statement?": "",
  "The amount of cash in the business bank account": "",
  "The total value of a company's assets": "",
  "The total income earned from selling goods or services before any expenses are deducted": "",
  "The total profit after all expenses are deducted": "",
  "Revenue is the total income generated from the sale of goods or services before any costs or expenses are subtracted. It is the starting point of the income statement.": "",
  "What does 'COGS' stand for?": "",
  "Cash on General Sales": "",
  "Cost of Goods Sold": "",
  "Cost of General Services": "",
  "Capital on Gross Sales": "",
  "COGS stands for Cost of Goods Sold, representing the direct costs attributable to producing or purchasing the goods a company sells during a period.": "",
  "What does 'gross margin' mean?": "",
  "The amount of debt a company carries": "",
  "The total revenue a business earns": "",
  "The difference between revenue and all expenses including taxes": "",
  "The percentage of revenue remaining after subtracting COGS": "",
  "Gross margin is expressed as a percentage and represents the portion of revenue that remains after the cost of goods sold is subtracted, calculated as (Revenue - COGS) / Revenue.": "",
  "What does 'net profit margin' mean?": "",
  "The ratio of assets to liabilities": "",
  "The percentage of revenue remaining after only COGS is deducted": "",
  "The total amount of revenue a business generates": "",
  "The percentage of revenue that remains as profit after ALL expenses, taxes, and interest are deducted": "",
  "Net profit margin measures what percentage of each dollar of revenue translates into actual profit after all expenses (COGS, operating expenses, interest, and taxes) have been deducted.": "",
  "What is 'depreciation' in accounting?": "",
  "The interest paid on borrowed money for equipment purchases": "",
  "A cash payment made monthly for equipment repairs": "",
  "An increase in the market value of an asset over time": "",
  "The gradual allocation of a long-term asset's cost over its useful life as a non-cash expense": "",
  "Depreciation is an accounting method that systematically spreads the cost of a tangible long-term asset (like machinery or vehicles) over its estimated useful life, reducing reported profit without an actual outflow of cash.": "",
  "What does 'contribution margin' mean?": "",
  "The selling price per unit minus the variable cost per unit": "",
  "The net income divided by total assets": "",
  "The total fixed costs of a business": "",
  "The total revenue divided by the number of employees": "",
  "Contribution margin is the amount each unit sold contributes toward covering fixed costs and generating profit, calculated as selling price per unit minus variable cost per unit.": "",
  "What does 'operating leverage' refer to?": "",
  "The amount of debt used to finance operations, based on conventional assumptions about leverage": "",
  "The ratio of fixed costs to variable costs in a business's cost structure, which amplifies profit changes as revenue changes": "",
  "The number of products a business sells, as conventional leverage theory would suggest": "",
  "The total amount of inventory on hand under most circumstances involving leverage": "",
  "Operating leverage describes how a company's cost structure (specifically its mix of fixed vs. variable costs) affects profitability. High operating leverage means small revenue changes lead to large profit swings.": "",
  "What is the 'bottom line' on an income statement?": "",
  "Gross profit": "",
  "Revenue (sales)": "",
  "Net income (the final profit or loss after all expenses)": "",
  "Total assets minus total liabilities": "",
  "Net income is called the 'bottom line' because it literally appears as the last line on the income statement, representing the final profit or loss after all revenues and expenses are accounted for.": "",
  "What does 'break-even point' mean in P&L analysis?": "",
  "The point at which a business decides to close": "",
  "The sales level at which total revenue exactly equals total costs, resulting in zero profit or loss": "",
  "The point at which a business has paid off all its long-term debt": "",
  "The maximum amount of revenue a business can generate": "",
  "The break-even point is the level of sales at which a business's total revenue equals its total costs (fixed + variable), meaning there is neither a profit nor a loss.": "",
  "What does 'trend analysis' mean when comparing P&L statements?": "",
  "Predicting stock prices based on chart patterns": "",
  "Comparing a single period's results to the industry average": "",
  "Examining financial data across multiple periods to identify patterns in revenue, costs, and profitability": "",
  "Calculating the total value of a company's assets over time": "",
  "Trend analysis involves comparing P&L statements from multiple periods (months, quarters, or years) to identify patterns and changes in revenue growth, cost management, and profitability over time.": "",
  "A clothing store has $350,000 in annual revenue, COGS of $140,000, and operating expenses of $120,000. What is the store's net profit before taxes?": "",
  "$90,000": "",
  "$140,000": "",
  "$230,000": "",
  "$210,000": "",
  "Gross profit = $350,000 - $140,000 = $210,000. Net profit before taxes = $210,000 - $120,000 = $90,000.": "",
  "A tech company has $800,000 in revenue and a 70% gross margin. If operating expenses are $300,000, what is the net income before taxes?": "",
  "$500,000": "",
  "$560,000": "",
  "$260,000": "",
  "Gross profit = $800,000 x 0.70 = $560,000. Net income before taxes = $560,000 - $300,000 = $260,000.": "",
  "A restaurant earns $500,000 in revenue. COGS is $175,000 and operating expenses total $225,000. What is the restaurant's net profit margin?": "",
  "35%": "",
  "20%": "",
  "45%": "",
  "65%": "",
  "Gross profit = $500,000 - $175,000 = $325,000. Net profit = $325,000 - $225,000 = $100,000. Net profit margin = $100,000 / $500,000 = 20%.": "",
  "A furniture maker sells tables for $200 each with a variable cost of $90 per table. Fixed costs are $55,000 per month. How many tables must be sold to break even?": "",
  "611 tables": "",
  "275 tables": "",
  "500 tables": "",
  "400 tables": "",
  "Contribution margin per table = $200 - $90 = $110. Break-even units = $55,000 / $110 = 500 tables per month.": "",
  "A SaaS company has monthly revenue of $120,000, COGS of $18,000, and operating expenses of $85,000. What is its gross margin percentage and net profit?": "",
  "Gross margin 90%, net profit $25,000": "",
  "Gross margin 85%, net profit $17,000": "",
  "Gross margin 70%, net profit $36,000": "",
  "Gross margin 85%, net profit $35,000": "",
  "Gross profit = $120,000 - $18,000 = $102,000. Gross margin = $102,000 / $120,000 = 85%. Net profit = $102,000 - $85,000 = $17,000.": "",
  "A business had revenue of $600,000 in Year 1 and $720,000 in Year 2. COGS increased from $240,000 to $324,000 over the same period. How did the gross margin change?": "",
  "Stayed the same at 60%": "",
  "Decreased from 60% to 55%": "",
  "Decreased from 65% to 55%": "",
  "Increased from 55% to 60%": "",
  "Year 1 gross margin = ($600K - $240K) / $600K = 60%. Year 2 gross margin = ($720K - $324K) / $720K = $396K / $720K = 55%. The gross margin declined by 5 percentage points, indicating COGS grew faster than revenue.": "",
  "A coffee shop has $8,000/month fixed costs. Each drink has a selling price of $5 and a variable cost of $1.50. The shop currently sells 3,000 drinks per month. What is its monthly profit and margin of safety in units?": "",
  "Profit $2,500, margin of safety 715 units": "",
  "Profit $2,500, margin of safety about 714 units": "",
  "Profit $2,500, margin of safety 2,286 units": "",
  "Profit $2,500, margin of safety 714 units": "",
  "CM per drink = $5.00 - $1.50 = $3.50. Total CM = 3,000 x $3.50 = $10,500. Profit = $10,500 - $8,000 = $2,500. BEP = $8,000 / $3.50 ≈ 2,286 units. Margin of safety = 3,000 - 2,286 = about 714 units above break-even.": "",
  "A company buys equipment for $60,000 with a 5-year useful life and no salvage value (straight-line depreciation). If annual revenue is $200,000, COGS is $90,000, and other operating expenses total $80,000, what is the annual net profit before taxes?": "",
  "$30,000": "",
  "$42,000": "",
  "$18,000": "",
  "$110,000": "",
  "Annual depreciation = $60,000 / 5 = $12,000. Gross profit = $200,000 - $90,000 = $110,000. Total operating expenses = $80,000 + $12,000 = $92,000. Net profit before taxes = $110,000 - $92,000 = $18,000.": "",
  "A subscription box company earns $40 per box with a variable cost of $22. Fixed costs are $54,000 per month. The company wants a target profit of $18,000 per month. How many boxes must it sell?": "",
  "4,500 boxes": "",
  "3,000 boxes": "",
  "3,600 boxes": "",
  "4,000 boxes": "",
  "Contribution margin per box = $40 - $22 = $18. Units needed = (Fixed costs + Target profit) / CM = ($54,000 + $18,000) / $18 = $72,000 / $18 = 4,000 boxes.": "",
  "A business with high operating leverage has $200,000 in fixed costs and low variable costs (10% of revenue). If revenue increases from $500,000 to $600,000, by how much does profit increase?": "",
  "$50,000": "",
  "$60,000": "",
  "$100,000": "",
  "At $500K revenue: Variable costs = $50K, Fixed costs = $200K, Profit = $500K - $50K - $200K = $250K. At $600K revenue: Variable costs = $60K, Fixed costs = $200K, Profit = $600K - $60K - $200K = $340K. Profit increase = $340K - $250K = $90K. A 20% revenue increase caused a 36% profit increase, demonstrating high operating leverage.": ""
}